  "Idea": "We propose a novel architecture called the Game-Informed Mixture Density Network (GIMDN), a multi-branch neural framework that integrates differentiable game-theoretic modules with deep product embeddings to model the full probability distribution of auction durations in dynamic online markets. Unlike prior methods that use game-theoretic outputs as static features, our approach embeds simplified Bayes-Nash equilibrium solvers as differentiable layers within the network, allowing gradients from real auction outcomes to fine-tune theoretical assumptions—effectively learning 'correction factors' for rationality violations such as overbidding or delayed entry. These corrected strategic signals are then combined with multimodal product embeddings (text, image, category) in a mixture density network that outputs a mixture of Gaussians representing the likely duration distribution. Crucially, we introduce an attention-based gating mechanism that learns to weigh the contribution of each branch (strategic vs. semantic) per auction instance, enabling post-hoc interpretation of whether duration uncertainty stems more from strategic unpredictability or product ambiguity. We further incorporate temporal context via a lightweight RNN over recent market states, allowing adaptation to non-stationarities like seasonal demand shifts or platform policy changes. This fusion enables both high predictive accuracy and economic interpretability—bridging the gap between structural modeling and black-box prediction. The model can be used not only for forecasting but also for counterfactual analysis, such as estimating how changing reserve prices or entry fees would affect expected duration and revenue under bounded rationality. By aligning machine learning with economic principles in a trainable, transparent way, GIMDN offers a new paradigm for modeling human-in-the-loop systems where theory and data must co-adapt.",
