  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework called Causal Graph-Informed Mixture Density Network (CG-MDN), a dynamically coupled, multi-branch architecture that jointly learns interpretable auction duration distributions by co-evolving game-theoretic beliefs and multimodal product representations within a latent interaction graph. Unlike prior approaches that treat game-theoretic predictions as exogenous features or use static embeddings, CG-MDN introduces a bidirectional refinement loop between a differentiable Bayesian game module and a modality-fused product encoder. Specifically, the product encoder (using BERT, CLIP-ViT, and category hierarchies) generates an initial value distribution prior over bidders, which is fed into a differentiable first-price auction solver based on approximate Bayes-Nash equilibrium computation via implicit differentiation. Crucially, the strategic outputs (e.g., expected entry times, bid intensity) are then projected back into the embedding space through a cross-modal transformer, allowing the product representation to be refined by 'strategic feedback'—for instance, learning that certain visual cues correlate with aggressive bidding even if text descriptions are neutral. These co-adapted signals are integrated into a dynamic interaction graph where nodes represent bidders and items, and edges encode learned competitive affinities updated via a temporal GNN. The graph evolves over auction stages using bidding event sequences, enabling non-stationary modeling of entrant clustering and competition heating. A mixture density network head then predicts the full duration distribution as a mixture of Gaussians, conditioned on both the final fused embedding and the graph's structural statistics (e.g., centrality, connectivity). To enable causal interpretation, we introduce a mediation analysis layer that decomposes the effect of input features (e.g., image resolution) into direct effects (on duration) versus indirect effects (mediated through s